  "published": "2019-10-04",
  "runtimeMin": 110,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Jason Concepcion trace the Joker from Batman #1 through the movies, then dig into Todd Phillips's film. Plus: Sean talks Lucy in the Sky with writer-director Noah Hawley.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Joker on screen, before Phillips",
      "note": "80 years of the character, four movie versions",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Man Who Laughs",
          "year": 1928,
          "note": "The Conrad Veidt silent film Bill Finger and Bob Kane cite as the source; Gwynplaine's permanent grin is the visual template for the Joker."
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Jack Nicholson plays to the rafters; Burton's version retcons the Joker as the man who shot Bruce Wayne's parents, an early fanboy-canon flashpoint."
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman Returns",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "Cited alongside the first as a strange, goofy cultural document, nothing like the later Marvel house style."
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman Begins",
          "year": 2005,
          "note": "The Nolan reboot, a hit whose success set up the anticipation for its sequel."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Dark Knight",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Heath Ledger's Joker, an unreliable narrator with no origin, reset the template and changed how the comics drew him too."
        },
        {
          "title": "Suicide Squad",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Jared Leto's muscular, tattooed Joker; a bungled, over-vain take with too many trace elements of Ledger to work."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Joker'",
      "note": "spoilers throughout",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Joker",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Todd Phillips's Travis Bickle riff, Joaquin Phoenix as Arthur Fleck. The hosts call it compelling and troubling, the truest screen version of the Joker as mentally ill, and a Trojan-horse 70s character study that only turns comic-book in its final act."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Noah Hawley on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Lucy in the Sky",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Hawley's feature debut, a fictionalized magic-realism riff on the Lisa Nowak astronaut story with Natalie Portman, built around a shifting aspect ratio."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
